{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/0022225470A/1930060901/0771.xml":{"full_text":"22\nwauna\nMLLES\nTREATY\nNEW YORK. June 9 (1.NJ3.).\nEditorial opinion among the lead\nin* newspapers of Germany today\nforecasts the speedy crystalizatton\nof a concerted demand for radical\nrevision of the terms of the treaty\n\u2022f Versailles.\n\u25a0Laying the groundwork for the\n\u2022lections which will foUow the con\nclusion of Field Marshal Paul Von\nHindenburg\u2019s term as President,\nnewspapers and politicians are\nputting this vexed subject before\nthe people of the country at every\nopportunity.\nf Wipe Out Stigma\n-With the new \u2018\u2022international\nism** provided Europe by the treat\nies of Locarno and the pact of\nFaris, leading opinion in Germany\ntends to the belief that the time\nIs-fast approaching when that na\ntion\u2019s demands for eradication of\nthe so-called \u201cstigma of Versailles**\ncan no longer go unheeded.\nFrom the moment the post-wax\nhysteria first began to subside, it\nhas been felt in Germany that\nthe world at large eventually\nwould recognize the countless\nfaults and unfairnesses which\nhave been alleged against the\nVenyiilles Treaty, drawn at a\ntime when war-hatred and vin\ndictlveness were still at their\nheight.\nWith the gradual washing\n\u2022way of prejudices and hatreds\nbom of conflict and with such\nstatesmen as Aristide Briand of\nFrance pleading for Pan-Eurc\npeanism of an encompassing\nscope. Germany feels she can soon\nrequest substitution of a more\nequable document for the present\ntreaty of Versailles.\nTreaty of Vengeance\nGermany has always held that\nVersailles was a Treaty of \u201cre\nvenge,\u201d formuated at a time\nWhen the Allied nations had no\ndesire other than to grind their\ndefeated enemies beneath their\nboot-heels. Germany accepted its\nterms, her leaders declare, \u201cunder\nduress.\u201d Historical \u201crevisionists\u201d\nof every nation\u2014those who are\nrecasting the causes of the world\nwar in such a manner as to re\nmove a great deal, if not all of\nthe blame from Germany\u2019s sol\ndiers. agree that the Versailles\nterms are too harsh and too vin\ndictive to remain in force for\nver.\nOUTHICLINK\nSEEN IN URGTIC\nNEW YORK, June 9 (U.S.).\n>*nud Rasmussen, arctic explorer,\nbelieves the Esquimaux are close\n17 related to the Neolithic men,\nvho once carved themselves\nl omes in the \u201ccaves\u201d of Europe,\nf.e is so convinced of this he will\nMik financial backing from\n/.merica, Soviet Russia and\nScandinavian countries for an\nexpedition to develop the idea.\nHis plans were made public\nzesterday by his daughter, Miss\nianne Rasmussen, who arrived on\nthe Scandinavian American liner\nUnited States. Miss Rasmussen\nMid her father would come here\nnext winter.\nThe daughter pointed out the\ngreat resemblance between uten\nsils unearthed in the caves of\nFrance and those used by the\nEsquimaux as tending to sup\nport her father\u2019s theory.\nBoat Line to Aid\ni Casualty Hospital\nPlans for a Casualty Hospital\nbenefit day on the steamer City\nof Washington, June 24, were an\nnounced last night by Roscoe Fer\ntich, chairman of the hospital\u2019s\ncampaign executive committee.\nThe entire proceeds of a moon\nlight trip to Piney Point that\nnight will be donated to the hos\npital\u2019s building and equipment\nliind by the Wilson Lines, opera\ntors pf the boat.\nE. 8. Wilson, jr., representing\nthe owners, said arrangements\n\u2022re being made for a program of\ndancing and music. The sale of\ntickets for the affair will be\nhandled by the membership com\nmittee of the Board of Trade.\nOld Proverb Proved\nBy Death of Woman\nPKRUB, June 9 (IH.S.) .\u2014\u201cWho\nsoever washes his linen during\nHoly Week, shall wash his wind\ning sheet,\u201d affirms an old prov\nerb of Burgundy. It came true\nphen Madame Gaulier, a widow\nliving near Dijon, was drowned\nwhile washing her clothes in a\nsmall pond.\nTrying to catch a piece of linen\nwhich was floating away, the\nwidow\u2019s wooden sabots slipped on\nthe wet grass. She fell in and\nwas drowned before anyone heard\nher cries for help. At home four\nsmall children were waiting for\nher return.\n$5,000,000 Highway\nProgram Under Way\nATLANTA, June 9 (IK.S.).\u2014\n4.* $5,000,000 highway program in\nGeorgia had been agreed to ac\ncording to Highway Board Chair\nman J. W. Barnett, who recently\nreturned here from Washington\nwhere he conferred with Federal\nauthorities.\nTh* program will be carried\nMH th the near future.\nSOVIET IMPORT\nBANNINB\nASKED\nBy authority of Roy C. Haines,\nexecutive vice president of the\nAnthracite Cooperative Associa\ntion. of Wilkes-Barre, Pa., the text\nof its protest against the admis\nsion of Russian Soviet coal duty\nfree, was made public here yes\nterday.\nThe petition was made to Secre\ntary of the Treasury Mellon, Sec\nretary of Labor Davis and Secre\ntary of Commerce Lamont, it is\nbacked by the Anthracite Opera\ntors of Pennsylvania and by the\nUnited Mine Workers of America.\nUp to President\nIt asks a presidential proclama\ntion excluding the Russian coal,\nwhich is being produced, shipped\nto Boston and sold in the New\nEngland markets at 11 a ton less\nthan the American operators can\nsell it.\nThe petition requests that the\nthree' Cabinet officers \u201cimme\ndiately set in operation the neces\nsary steps for the exclusion of\nRussian anthracite coal, mined,\nprocessed and. transported, di\nrectly or indirectly, by the Soviet\ngovernment.\u201d\nThe petition contains the as\nsertion that the Soviet govern\nment \u201ccontrols the price of labor,\nthe hours Os work, living con\nditions of the miners: prescribes\ndiscipline of all workers, fixes\nthe yearly quota of production,\nand subsidizes the transporta\ntion to foreign market.\u201d\nPrecludes Competition\nIt adds:\n\u201cCompared with American\nwages and expression of living,\nthis presents a condition impos\nsible for American operators to\ncompete with, and precludes suc\ncessful competition by American\nrail freight carriers, even though\nRussian anthracite travels to\nBoston 18 miles for every mile\nof Pennsylvania anthracite.\u201d\nRussian niners\u2019 wages are from\n17 cents a day to $32.50 a month,\nand to compete with Russian con\nditions. Pennsylvania miners\nwould have to quarter their pres\nent wage scale, it is contended.\nIt is further maintained that\nthe dumping of the Soviet coal\nis part \u201cof a wilful, malicious and\npremeditated scheme to destroy\ncompetitive labor and industry in\nall foreign countries where Soviet\nproducts are to be entered.\u201d\nSan Quentin Inmates\nWould Woo Muses\nSACRAMENTO. Calif.. June 9\n(I.NJ3.).\u2014Stone walls do not a\nprison make\u2014not when the muses\nof spring flit from pastoral glades\ninto the drab confines of San\nQuentin prison.\nAll of which was proved today\nwhen A. J. Shuder, new San Quen\ntin educational director, an\nnounced that more tl\u201e.n 40\nvicts have applied for special in\nstruction in versification.\nShuder, conferring with Vierling\nKersey, State educational director,\nconsidered the request favorably,\nand so the poetry urge in San\nQuentin will be fathered.\nChipmunks Blamed\nFor Theft of Auto\nGRIDLEY, Calif., June 9 (IN.\nS.) .\u2014Chipmunks were given the\nblame for the theft of an auto\nmobile key by Frank J. Cowan\nand George Stillson, both of\nGridley.\nThey parked their car in the\nwoods at Chapparal while fishing,\nhaving placed the key, attached\nto a leather tag, in the lee of a\nrock.\nOn their return, the car was in\ntact, but the key gone. A colony\nof chipmunks, chattering merrily\nin the trees, seemed to be laugh\ning.\nWins Until He Shows\nProfits, Then Loses\nCINCINNATI, June 9 (INS.).\nMatching dollars is excellent di\nversion. Amsey Hodge, of West\nHamlin. W. Va., will tell you,\nprovided you are winning and\u2014\nyour victim doesn\u2019t run off with\nthe pot.\nHodge recently matched dollars\nhere with a local \u201ccity slicker\u201d\nand after winning all the way,\nrevealed $l5O. The temptation\nwas evidently. too much for the\n\u201cslicker,\u201d who snatched the\npurse and fled.\nWomen Clubs Irked\nAt City Billboards\nCHICAGO, June 9 (1.N.5.).\u2014\nThose tall, ugly, over bearing si\nlent venders, popularly known as\nbillboards, are in the way here to\nday.\nThis is the viewpoint of a\ngroup of women\u2019s clubs in the\ncity who are urging the removal\nof all billboards because they lend\nnothing to the enhancement of\nlocal civic beauty, obstruct the\nview, and not only serve to\ncheapen the property which\nthey stand, but too often suc\nceed in driving citizens from lo\ncating homes near them.\nCITIZENS TO SEE FILM\nThe American University Park\nCitizens Association will have a\nmotion picture program at its\nnext regular meeting Wednesday\nevening at 8 o\u2019clock in Hurst Hall\nof American University, Massa\nchusetts and Nebraska Avenues\nNorthwaat.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nROMPING\nAHOUNDTHE\nRADIO\nDIAISZ? J.\nCesar Baerchinger, well known\nnewspaperman and authority on\nmusic, has been appointed London\nOn With the Dance\n4:00 p. m\u2014-D an c Ing Troubadors\n(WMAU.\n4:30 p. m.\u2014Tea Timers (WHO.\n10:13 p.m.\u2014Yoeng\u2019e Orchestra\n(WMAL).\n10:88 p. m\u2014Glee letaad Caelao\nOrchestra (WMAL).\n11 :08 p. m.\u2014Weodmansten Orches\ntra (WMAL)t Edge\nwater Reach OrchMtra\n(WRC).\ncorrespondent for the Columbia\nBroadcasting System in connec\ntion with a program of interna\ntional news events to be broad\ncast direct from London to radio\nlisteners in the United States.\nMr. Saerchlnger is the first regu\nlar news correspondents assigned\nto a foreign country by a broad\ncasting company.\nThe honor of being the first\nspecial correspondent goes to Fred\nerick William Wile, also of Col\numbia, who covered the Five\nPower Naval Parley earlier this\nyear, Mr. Saerchlnger, however,\nwill be a permanent representa\ntive.\nAt 5:30 o\u2019clock this evening the\nWestern High School Senior Glee\nClub will give a concert over\nWMAL. Eldridge Church, presi\ndent of the club, was the leader\nof the winning Company H in the\nrecent high school cadet drills.\nYoung Church will be the saxa\nphone soloist this evening.\n\u201cLanterns That Will Signal the\nReturn of Prosperity\u201d is the sub\nject of the first of a series of\ntalks by Merryle Stanley Rukey\nser, contributing editor of the\nIndustrial Digest and recognized\nauthority on financial matters,\nwhose columns are a daily fea\nture of The Washington Herald.\nMr. Rukeyser\u2019s inaugurating talk\nwill be broadcast this evening at\n7:15 o\u2019clock over the Columbia\nSystem.\nAs financial editor of many\nnewspapers, Mr. Rukeyser has\nhad an opportunity to familiarize\nhimself with the investmen* prob\nlems of the public, which is the\nfield his radio work will em\nbrace.\nA concert of Latin-American\nmusic played by the combined\nUnited States service bands will\nbe broadcast over WRC this\nevening at 10 o\u2019clock. The band\nconsists of picked musicians from\nthe Army, Navy and Marine\nBands.\n3 P. M.\nW AML \u2014The United States\nNavy Band, under the direction\nof Lieut. Charles Benter, will\nbe on the air. The concert will\nbe picked up at the Navy Yard\nat Washington.\n6 P M\nWRC\u2014 Starting with a song by\nthe eighteenth century composer,\nChristoph Willibald Gluck, Rosalie\nWolfe will move along a century\nto one by Luigi Denza who was\nbom in 1848 and close with two\ntwentieth century numbers by\nEmmerich Kalman and Irving\nI Berlin.\n8:15 P. M.\nWRC \u2014\u201cMussolini\u2019s bellicose\nspeech in Florence the middle of\nMay has been interpreted in some\nQuarters as a direct challenge to\nFrance\u201d, says James G. McDonald,\nwho will take up the Franco-\nItalian impasse in his talk, The\nWorld Today.\n8:38 P. M.\nWRC\u2014Byrd\u2019s recent flight over\nthe South Pole area has fur\nnished R. L. \u201cBelieve It or Not\u201d\nRipley with many new \"queeriosi\nties\u201d which he plans to tell dur\ning the Colonial Beaconlights*\nprogram.\n7:30 P. M.\nWMAL\u2014Merle Johnston and\nhis CeCo Couriers will preset\nprogram of dance music. \u00bb.<mry\nBurbig, humorist, will also be\nheard on the program.\n9 P. M.\nWRC\u2014That very popular negro\nspiritual \u201cSwing Low Sweet\nChariot,\u201d will be one of the fea\ntures heard when the Ovaltine\nPlane of Dreams starts on its\nmusical flight this evening.\n9:30 P. M.\nWRC\u2014Fred Waldner, tenor:\nBuryi Retting and Dick Platt,\npiano duo and Adolphe Dumont\u2019s\nconcert orchestra Interpret the\nfavorite selections of the \u201cmusic\nlover\u201d in the Sign of the Shell\nprogram.\nWMAL\u2014Mr. and Mrs. Jesse\nCranford will play their latest\ntwin organ arrangement of Mrs.\nCrawford\u2019s composition \u201cThe\nMoonlight Reminds Me of You.\u201d\nPaul Small, tenor, will contribute\nto the program, which is to be\nannounced by Louis A. Witten.\nTrout Transferred\nTo Deeper Streams\nSTAUNTON. Va., June 9.\u2014Seven\nhundred and fifty mountain trout\nisolated in shallow pools this week\nwere transferred into deeper pools\nin the mountain streams of the\nShenandoah Mountains by As\nsistant Game Warden Wade Faw\nley and Supervisor Lewis F. Mil\nler. it has been learned here.\nMountain streams have almost\ndisappeared as result of the long\nspring drought in this section\nand many lovers of the fishing\nSport are said to be assisting tn\ntraaatamn* trout to deeper water*\nLOCAL STATIONS\nmw\u2014 wmmu\u2014 .w ii.\n12) 19\u2014Palais d'Or OrchMtra.\n11:44\u2014Nationa Farm an* Roma\nHour\u2014epeakara: A. F Sievers,\nJ. 1. Webb and F. X. Uhlar.\nI:lo\u2014Organ Recital from tha Kitt\nstudios.\nI:lo\u2014American Foundation for tha\nBllndJ\n3:oo\u2014Moxie Hoi tcm Hour.\n1:11\u2014U. 8. Army Band. Wm. J.\nStannard. loader. broadcast\nfrom Washington Barracks.\nI:2l\u2014lnternationa! Viewpolnte by\nWalter Lippman, Chief Edl.\ntorlai writer of N